<p>
In summary, <m>f</m> is increasing on the set <m>(-\infty,-1)\cup (3,\infty)</m> and is decreasing on the set <m>(-1,1)\cup (1,3)</m>. Since at <m>x=-1</m>, the sign of \fp<nbsp />switched from positive to negative, <xref ref="thm_first_der">Theorem</xref> states that <m>f(-1)</m> is a relative maximum of <m>f</m>. At <m>x=3</m>, the sign of \fp<nbsp />switched from negative to positive, meaning <m>f(3)</m> is a relative minimum. At <m>x=1</m>, <m>f</m> is not defined, so there is no relative extrema at <m>x=1</m>.
</p>
